Practice Problem 1: Syntax Match <p>If <code>ptr</code> is a pointer to <code>x</code>, which of these is true? A. <code>ptr</code> stores the value of <code>x</code>. B. <code>*ptr</code> is the same as <code>x</code>. C. <code>&amp;ptr</code> is the same as <code>x</code>.</p> Solution <p>B. </p> <p><code>ptr</code> stores the address of <code>x</code>. When you use the <code>*</code> (dereference) operator, you are looking at the value stored at that address, which is <code>x</code>.</p> Practice Problem 2: Changing Values <p><pre><code>int a = 10;
int b = 20;
int *p = &amp;a;
*p = b;
</code></pre> After this code runs, what is the value of <code>a</code>?</p> Solution <p>20. </p> <p>The pointer <code>p</code> was pointing to <code>a</code>. When you ran <code>*p = b</code>, you told the computer: "Go to the address stored in <code>p</code> (which is <code>a</code>'s house) and put the value of <code>b</code> (20) inside."</p>
